nib.text:
Nine people were detained by police early Friday morning during a demonstration near the scene of a U.S. Marshal-involved shooting in Uptown, officials said. 

At around 12:30 a.m., a large group assembled near West
Lake Street and Fremont Avenue, where hours prior members of a U.S. Marshals task force fatally shot a man wanted for an illegal firearm warrant. 

Citizen user video showed some objects had been set on fire in a crosswalk as the group gathered. 

The MPD reported that as the night went on, several assaults and looting occurred in the area, prompting a response by the MPD. 

The report stated officers were permitted to use tear gas and marker rounds, however, officers resorted to other non-lethal methods. The report did not specify what methods were used. 

Nine people were arrested and held in the Hennepin County Adult Detention Center. Charges included assaults, arson, rioting, and destruction of property. 

Detectives are continuing to search for people who were involved in the activity.

nib.text:
One person was killed in a shooting involving U.S. Marshals Service task force members in Uptown Minneapolis Thursday afternoon, officials said. 

According to the U.S. Marshals Service, law enforcement officers were operating at a parking ramp near West Lake Street and Fremont Avenue South around 2:10 p.m.

Task force members were attempting to apprehend a suspect who was wanted on an illegal firearm warrant.

Officials said the suspect was in a parked car with a woman and was not complying with commands.

According to a statement from the USMS, the suspect allegedly fired a handgun from inside the vehicle and was shot by task force members.

Officers attempted life-saving measures, but medics pronounced the suspect dead at the scene.

The woman was treated for minor injuries from glass debris.

According to [local media](https://www.kare11.com/article/news/local/uptown-minneapolis-shooting/89-070ac371-5567-4a36-9d18-a7abc7e048a7) witnesses reported hearing 10 to 15 gunshots.

A handgun and bullet casings were recovered from the driver's seat of the suspect's vehicle.

Various law enforcement agencies responded to the area including the Minneapolis Police Department (MPD), the Hennepin County Sheriff’s Office, and the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, and Firearms (ATF).

The Minnesota Bureau of Criminal Apprehension is in charge of the ongoing investigation.

According to a statement from the Minnesota Department of Public Safety, the U.S. Marshal Service does not allow the use of body cameras for officers serving on its North Star Fugitive Task Force, and there is no video footage of the incident from officers or law enforcement dashboard cameras. 

Later that night, a number of protests took place throughout Minneapolis, which multiple local news sources reported were related to the shooting.
